,Recommended,242550,15406310,"Posted: 16 April, 2015",all,MerlinPants,"The great:  Originality seeps from every pore of this game.  The artwork is phenominal, the level design is smart, and the music is lively and joyous.  Every character is quirky and fun, even if they're not that different gameplay-wise.  Rayman Legends capitalizes on the simplicity of the platforming genre, and does it in an accessible, streamlined experience.The good:  The game modes.  When you finally exhaust the immense amount of levels, there is still more to do.  You can play a surprisingly intense round of Kung Foot, which is soccer meets the Matrix.  You can play some levels from the previous games.  You can also do some challenges that are devilishly tricky.  Obviously, this stuff was added as an afterhtought, and it isn't as fleshed out as the main levels, but it was a smart afterthought, because it is still quite fun.The bad:  It's an Ubisoft game for PC, so you know what that means.  Yup, you're gonna have to deal with the annoyance of Uplay.  Booting up the game from Steam only to have it open Uplay and update itself, and then slowly clunk you into what you actually wanted to do in the first place, which is play the game.  It's unfortunate that this exists, because the developers had nothing to do with this decision and it's all Ubisoft's fault.  Bah humbug.Overall, this is a must own for lovers of local co-op and/or platformers.  It has a unique charm about it that is unseen elsewhere, and it's worth dealing with Ubisoft's incompetence to get to the reward of this phenominal experience.Verdict:  Buy it for any price, you won't be sorry."
