76561197999170548,Recommended,242550,8495021,"Posted: 1 January, 2014",all,Подлый Негодяй,"Triple-A TitleThere are many cartoony indie side-scrollers available on Steam, most costing under $15, so $40 for Rayman Legends may seem steep. However, this game is much bigger and more detailed than most of the indie titles. The game appears to be bigger than its predecessor, Rayman Origins, as well. There are 60 main stages, ""Back To Origins"" levels re-playing some Origins levels, rotating daily and weekly challenges, and more little stuff. All of that adds up to a lot of gameplay, especially considering you'll want to go re-play stages multiple times to get the fastest time, or collect all the things.Speaking of which, this game is a collector's paradise. Every corner of the game is littered with collectable items, which the game constantly tallies and rewards you with new levels and characters. There are a lot more characters in Legends than there were in Origins, and they all have their own amusing animations.This game is highly polished on every level. From the character animations, to the visual style, to the music, this game is a joy to behold, unless you're only interested in the brown-grey wash gritty shooters. In a way the game is visually old-school, in that every level has a theme(swamp, fire, etc.), but it's always interesting to see new scenery, and it's all beautifully drawn. I can't tell for certain, but I'm pretty sure the soundrack is recorded with a live orchestra. The resulting sound appropriately zany, but rich and authentic at the same time. Again, this is on a level beyond what an indie side-scroller can offer.The gameplay is fairly old-school as well, in good ways and bad. While the simple, classic controls never seem to get old, the game can also be very demanding, requiring split-second precision. If you want to get a perfect run through a stage you pretty much have to retry and retry, and basically memorize every button press, or every attack in a boss fight. While it can be frustrating, there are relatively few moments where you're bottlenecked; you don't have to grind unless you're a perfectionist.I was happy to get the game for $20 during the holiday sale, and I think the game is absolutely worth it at that price. Is it worth $40, though? I'm inclined to say yes, simply because of the amount of content and the level of polish throughout. This is a full-size game, and it comes at a full-size price. If you can get it at a discount it starts to be a great deal."
