,Recommended,242550,10825004,"Posted: 26 June, 2014",all,Jachymor,"So far I got 3/6 worlds finished, not counting the Origin Worlds that you can unlock and not counting any challenges or hidden areas. This game continues where Origins left - gameplay and ""story"" alike. It also adds some things to the formula, like your pixie helper you can raise bridges, cut ropes and eat cake. Also you can be turned into a duck or infiltrate a James-Bondian underwater lair. So far, so Rayman.If you played Origins, you already know the new Rayman is a splendid combination of Mario, Sonic and Rayman games in terms of Jump'n'Run, Speedrunning and Wackyness. Legends doubles the fun with perfectly speedrunnable maps, many secrets to find and even Rythm levels. The game is smooth, beautiful and has even more gorgeous soundtracks the the previous title. To the less important additions count a strange monster collecting game and ticket rubbing.Rayman Origins is, in my opinion, the best Jump'n'Run in history. Rayman Legends comes close, but despite the greatness of the levels, the less punishing checkpoint system and the TLC overall, I feel slightly disconnected from the overall story. You can skip worlds and levels and do them in your own order (with boss and rythm levels being an exception) and the feeling of advancement is overshadowed by the ""Do whatever you please"" attitude. It is probably more fitting for a Rayman game, but Legends cannot quite grasp the tone like Origins did it, where the the transition between the worlds was smooth and logical.P.S.: James Bondian Laser Security System can be run through without you needed to stop which felt so forking awesome!"
