76561198104037772,Recommended,242550,16429145,"Posted: 15 June, 2015",all,renswisse1987,"Rayman is an interesting fella. He doesn't have a neck or limbs, but that doesn't prevent him from being a platform household name. His first game back in 1995 was full of original gameplay concepts that kept you hooked, despite the game's brutal difficulty. The game was such as succes that sequels followed after a few years. As great as those were, they were subject to the '3D rule' that departed from the classic side-scrolling worlds of old and offered 3D worlds instead.After the succes of games like New Super Mario Bros. in recent years, many platformer series started to explore the good old realm of 2D platforming again, a realm lost somewhere in the late 90s. Rayman did it with the fantastic Rayman Origins (also on Steam, check it out if you have not already). Origins was a welcome game in 2011, as we hadn't really seen Ubisoft's mascot in a while. It was an old-fashioned 2D platformer like the 1995 classic, but also brought in elements from the 3D sequels. What Origins did better than many games in the new generation of sidescrollers, though, was that it also had new additions to the series of its own.Other genre icons often kept innovation limited to 3D games, using the 2D entries to provide a nostalgic feel of familiarity. Origins was different. It was quirkier, more experimental, more anarchic in both gameplay and visuals, while also remaining true to its 90s roots.Building from the same engine as Origins, Legends controls and feels very similar to its predecessor, yet somehow it also manages to feel fresh. What makes it so fun is that each level feels different and new gameplay elements are contstantly added, adding additional depth to the cleverly designed levels. At one point you're jumping through the desert along the beat of 'Eye of the Tiger' while later you might find yourself running vertically along a wall being chased by dragons. For a true fun fest you can gather some friends around and play cooperatively. Too bad there's still no online mode for this.This is especially painful when you notice how big and robust of a package Legends otherwise is. There's plenty of  unlockable characters, which unfortunately have very little variation in both appearance and gameplay. More interesting are the levels you can unlock. Additional levels are unlocked if you collect more fairies and free more Teensies (your friends). The game has new weekly challenges to satisfy even ardent platform fans. The game even throws in a selection of the best levels from Origins as an unlockable extra. These are tweaked just so that you don't quite get the same experience as in the previous game.The presentation is even better than in Origins. While I found that game to be one of the prettiest I ever played, Legends is even more detailed and dynamic than its predecessor, without changing much in terms of Rayman's distinct style. I could not have imagined a 2D game even more stunning than Origins, but Legends somehow manages it. Legends truly shows that there's really no limit to what can be achieved with today's 2D graphics in HD resolutions. The musical score is gorgeous and fully orchestrated. The tunes are a little similar, even when compared with Origins. There could have been a little more variety. Still, this is a soundtrack with a level of quality that most platformers don't have, just like in 1995.Rayman Legends is just sheer fun, especially with friends. While not a drastic departure from the already impressive Origins, Legends still manages to provide a bigger, more polished package. If you can look past the lack of variety in characters or the lack of an online coop mode, there's is simply no better side-scrolling platformer available at the moment. This is the combination of art direction, gameplay and creativity that is rare in the genre these days. Rayman could just have taken the easy route and use the 'retro IS the appeal' mantra so common these days. Instead, Rayman Legends is also a modern game at the same time. Don't waste your time and money on the latest same old New Super Mario Bros. Rayman is where it's really at right now. Sorry, Nintendo, but Ubisoft beats you where you used to excel.9,5/10"
,Recommended,242550,10269802,"Posted: 28 May, 2014",all,Hunnybee2,"VERDICTBuy Now (9.6/10)Completion Time: 20-25 hoursBottom Line: ""This game is quite simply the best. Rayman is at it again""PROS+Level Design+Level Variety+SO MANY LEVELS+Really pretty+Hilarious+Awesome Music+Replay Value+The CreditsCONS-No Online Co-op-Uplay integration-The game endsREVIEWThis game is quite simply the best. Rayman is at it again as he traverses 80 creative and often hilarious levels to save the world from nightmares. You'll be swimming, flying, transforming and more through 8 incredibly stylish and unique worlds. With each level you will surely be trying something new, with a huge variety of gameplay mechanics involved.Level designs are incredibly fun and fast paced, including musical levels where your actions are synchronized with the music. While we're on this topic, the score is awesome. There is everything from tropical ukulele driven tunes to stealthy James Bond-esque ballads. Did I mention this game is really pretty? Especially the remastered throwback levels where the detail is immense.Don't even get me started on replay value. Not only are there 120 levels to master, but in each there are plenty of collectables and secret areas. Online challenges also ensure the introduction of fresh new content EVERY DAY. Finally, the ending includes the most creative credits sequence I have ever seen. Never have credits been so much fun.There are only two minor gripes I have with the game. There is no online multiplayer co-op, and there is Uplay integration, meaning you must create a Ubisoft account in order to start the game. Otherwise this game is absolutely brilliant."
